    "\n",
    "# Read the images\n",
    "barbie_ken = io.imread('images/barbie_ken.png')\n",
    "oppenheimer = io.imread('images/oppenheimer.jpeg')\n",
    "\n",
    "red_channel = oppenheimer[:, :, 0]\n",
    "green_channel = barbie_ken[:, :, 1]\n",
    "blue_channel = barbie_ken[:, :, 2]\n",
    "\n",
    "print(red_channel)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Print the shape and data of the images\n",
    "print('Barbie_ken type:{}'.format(barbie_ken.dtype))\n",
    "print('Barbie_ken shape:{}'.format(barbie_ken.shape))\n",
    "\n",
    "print('\\n')\n",
    "\n",

    "# Visualize both images in one single figure using subplots\n",

   "source": [
    "# Your solution here\n",
    "from skimage.transform import resize\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "\n",
    "# Load the images\n",
    "barbie_land = io.imread('images/barbieland.jpeg')\n",
    "opp = io.imread('images/oppenheimer_transparent_background.png')\n",
    "\n",
    "# Resize the oppenheimer image to half the size of barbie_land\n",
    "opp_new_shape = (barbie_land.shape[0]//2, barbie_land.shape[1]//2)\n",
    "\n",
    "opp_resized = resize(opp, opp_new_shape, mode='constant')\n",
    "\n",
    "# Get the alpha channel (transparency) from the RGBA image\n",
    "alpha_channel = opp_resized[:, :, 3]\n",
    "\n",
    "# Overlay the resized oppenheimer image on top of barbie_land without transparency\n",
    "barbie_opp = barbie_land.copy()\n",
    "\n",
    "#barbie_opp = np.where(alpha_channel == 0, opp_resized, barbie_land)\n"
   ]

    "## Champions of the world"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Spain's women's football team made history by clinching their first-ever World Cup victory, and now it's your turn to join in the celebration! Sometimes, the most thrilling moments require us to dig deeper and count the individuals who make it all possible. In this exercise, we will segment the team applying the techniques that you've learned in class.\n",
    "\n",
    "![img](images/campeonas_2023.jpeg)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Ex.2.1) (2 points) Load the image ``images/campeonas_2023.jpeg`` and visualize it. Segment the image using the Felzenszwalb algorithm and determine which set of parameters is better: \n",
    "\n",
    "* parameters by default,\n",
    "* scale=50, sigma=2, min_size=500\n",
    "* scale=50, sigma=5, min_size=250 \n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "Visualize the original image, and the results of the segmentation in the same figure (1x4 grid).\n",
    "\n",
    "Make sure to answer:\n",
    "1. What are the different parameters doing?\n",
    "2. Comment the results and be explicit mentioning the best parameter set from the provided.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 37,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Auxiliar function\n",
    "def visualize(original, segmentation, label):\n",
    "    fig=plt.figure(figsize=(20,15))\n",
    "\n",
    "    \n",
    "    for i in range(len(segmentation)):\n",
    "        fig.add_subplot(1,4,i+1)\n",
    "\n",
    "        if(i != 0):\n",
    "            plt.imshow(mark_boundaries(original, segmentation[i])) \n",
    "        else:\n",
    "            plt.imshow(segmentation[i])\n",
    "            \n",
    "        plt.title(label[i])\n",
    "        plt.xticks([])\n",
    "        plt.yticks([])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 39,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 2000x1500 with 4 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# your solution\n",
    "from skimage.segmentation import felzenszwalb\n",
    "from skimage.segmentation import mark_boundaries\n",
    "# Your solution here\n",
    "\n",
    "# Load image\n",
    "champions = io.imread('images/campeonas_2023.jpeg')\n",
    "\n",
    "# Apply felzenszwalb\n",
    "champions_1 = felzenszwalb(champions)\n",
    "champions_2 = felzenszwalb(champions, scale=50, sigma=2, min_size=500)\n",
    "champions_3 = felzenszwalb(champions, scale=50, sigma=5, min_size=250)\n",
    "\n",
    "titles = [\n",
    "    'Original Image', 'Felenszwalbs default parameters'\n",
    "    , 'scale=50, sigma=2, min_size=500', 'scale=50, sigma=5, min_size=250'\n",
    "    ]\n",
    "\n",
    "# Lets visualize the images in a subplot\n",
    "visualize(champions, [champions, champions_1, champions_2, champions_3], titles)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "1. What are the different parameters doing?\n",
    "    - > scale: Controls the size of the segments (sets the segmentation level). Higher values result in larger segments. it defines the quantity and size of the clusters.\n",
    "    - > sigma: This value is used for smoothing the image before segmentation. Higher values will smooth more, potentially leading to larger segments. Basically defines the width of Gaussian kernel.\n",
    "    - > min_size: The minimum component size. It ensures that small regions get merged into larger ones.\n",
    "    \n",
    "2. Comment the results and be explicit mentioning the best parameter set from the provided.\n",
    "  > This is a quite subjective question and can vary based on the desired granularity of segmentation. From the example parameters provided, the middle set (scale=50, sigma=2, min_size=500) might give a good balance between detail and generalization. In comparison between the two sets, the scale parameter didn't change, but we applied more Gaussian smoothing with sigma=5. We also changed the min_size, which has ensured that smaller parts got merged into larger ones. But I strongly believe that having less smoothing and a larger min_size (middle set) provides a better segmentation."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Ex.2.2) (1.5 points) Segment the image using the SLIC algorithm and determine which set of parameters is better: \n",
    "\n",
    "* n_segments=25, compactness=5,sigma=1\n",
    "* n_segments=75, compactness=5,sigma=3 \n",
    "\n",
    "Visualize the original image and the result of the segmentation in the same figure (using subplots).\n",
    "\n",
    "Comment the results, make sure to explicitly mention the best set of parameters."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 40,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 2000x1500 with 3 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# your solution\n",
    "from skimage.segmentation import slic\n",
    "# Your solution here\n",
    "\n",
    "# your solution\n",
    "segments_slic_1 = slic(champions, n_segments=25, compactness=5, sigma=1, start_label=1)\n",
    "segments_slic_2 = slic(champions, n_segments=75, compactness=5, sigma=3, start_label=1)\n",
    "\n",
    "titles = [\n",
    "    'Original Image', 'n_segments=25, compactness=5,sigma=1', 'n_segments=75, compactness=5,sigma=3'\n",
    "    ]\n",
    "visualize(champions, [champions, segments_slic_1, segments_slic_2], titles)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "SLIC is based on the k-means clustering algorithm, considering both color and spatial domains. It initializes with seed points as cluster centers and iteratively refines clusters using a combined distance metric until convergence to a local minimum.\n",
    "\n",
    "## Parameters\n",
    "    The *n_segments* represents the approximate number of labels of the segmented image.\n",
    "\n",
    "    The _compactness_ balances the color proximity, with the higher values, it makes superpixel shapes more cubic as we can see in the first image.\n",
    "   \n",
    "    The _sigma_ defines the width of Gaussian kernel, it smoothes the image before the segmentation.\n",
    "    \n",
    "> From the results, the slic with 75 segments is the best, as its segmentation considered more features and the faces pretty well. This is highly related to the number of segments, since the compactness didn't change and the ammount of smoothing is not that different."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Ex.2.3) (2 points) Apply the Canny edge detector\n",
    "\n",
    "Do Canny edge detector in 2 ways: \n",
    "1. On a grayscale version of the image\n",
    "2. By channel and combine it. Make sure that your edges result is of (426, 640) dimensionalty with True/False (or equivalent numerically) values representing edges. \n",
    "\n",
    "Overlap your results on the original image, and show the following visualization:\n",
    "\n",
    "![img](images/canny.jpg)"
   ]
  },

     "data": {

   "source": [
    "# Your solution here\n",
    "from skimage.feature import canny\n",
    "from skimage.color import rgb2gray\n",
    "from skimage.segmentation import mark_boundaries\n",
    "\n",
    "gray_image = rgb2gray(champions)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Apply canny\n",
    "segments_canny_1 = canny(gray_image)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Apply canny by channel\n",
    "canny_R = canny(champions[:,:,0])\n",
    "canny_G = canny(champions[:,:,1])\n",
    "canny_B = canny(champions[:,:,2])\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "# Overlap the original image with canny's edges\n",
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(ncols=3, figsize=(16,16))\n",

    "ax[0].axis('off')\n",
    "\n",

    "ax[1].axis('off')\n",
    "\n",

    "ax[2].set_title('By channel canny')\n",
    "ax[2].axis('off')\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.show()"

    "## It is a dog... It is a cat.. It's a hybrid! \n",
    "\n",
    "<table>\n",
    "  <tr>\n",
    "    <td><img src=\"images/cat.jpg\" alt=\"Image 1\" style=\"width: 300px;\"/></td>\n",

   ]

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Ex.2.3) Create a cat dog hybrid (1.5 points) \n",
    "Read `images/dog.jpg` and `images/cat.jpg` and create a hybrid image where you see the dog from a closer view and the cat from afar. Display the result in gray scale, just as the examples provided. Use sigma = 6 for the smoothing and show your images plotted with a size of (20,20) and (2,2) width and height in inches *(figsize parameter in matplotlib)* so it can be seen the dog in the large image and the cat from the small one. Your results should  look like this:\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "<img src = images/hybrid_cat_dog.jpg width=\"400\">\n",
    "<img src = images/hybrid_cat_dog.jpg width=\"100\">"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 80,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 2000x2000 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 200x200 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "import skimage\n",
    "from skimage.filters import gaussian\n",
    "from skimage import img_as_float\n",
    "# Your solution here\n",
    "\n",
    "def apply_filters(image, lp_sigma=6):\n",
    "    image_float = img_as_float(image)\n",
    "    low_pass = gaussian(image_float, lp_sigma)\n",
    "    high_pass = image_float - low_pass\n",
    "    return low_pass, high_pass\n",
    "\n",
    "def create_hybrid_image(low_pass_img, high_pass_img):\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    Creates a hybrid image by adding the low-pass and high-pass filtered images.\n",
    "\n",
    "    Args:\n",
    "    - low_pass_img (ndarray): Image after applying low-pass filter.\n",
    "    - high_pass_img (ndarray): Image after applying high-pass filter.\n",
    "\n",
    "    Returns:\n",
    "    - ndarray: Hybrid image.\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    return low_pass_img + high_pass_img\n",
    "\n",
    "def resize_and_plot(images, titles, scale_factor):\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    Resize the provided images by the given scale factor and then plot them.\n",
    "\n",
    "    Args:\n",
    "    - images (list): List of images to resize and plot.\n",
    "    - titles (list): Titles for each of the images.\n",
    "    - scale_factor (float): Factor by which to resize the images.\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    fig, axarr = plt.subplots(ncols=len(images), figsize=(20, 8))\n",
    "    \n",
    "    for i, (img, title) in enumerate(zip(images, titles)):\n",
    "        # Ensure only the first 3 channels are used (RGB)\n",
    "        img = img[..., :3]\n",
    "        resized_img = transform.rescale(img, scale_factor, anti_aliasing=True)\n",
    "        axarr[i].imshow(resized_img, cmap='gray')\n",
    "        axarr[i].set_title(title)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    plt.show()\n",
    "\n",
    "# Load the images (they have the same shape)\n",
    "dog = io.imread('images/dog.jpg')\n",
    "cat = io.imread('images/cat.jpg')\n",
    "\n",
    "# Images to gray\n",
    "dog_gray = rgb2gray(dog)\n",
    "cat_gray = rgb2gray(cat)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Apply the smoothing and get the low and high pass\n",
    "dog_lp, dog_hp = apply_filters(dog_gray)\n",
    "cat_lp, cat_hp = apply_filters(cat_gray)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Create the hybrid image\n",
    "hybrid_image = create_hybrid_image(cat_lp, dog_hp)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Visualize the hybrid image\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(20,20))\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.subplot(1,2,1) # Plot of 1 row 2 columns\n",
    "plt.imshow(hybrid_image, cmap='gray')\n",
    "plt.axis('off') # Get rid of axis for the sake of clarity\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.show()\n",
    "\n",
    "# Visualize the hybrid image\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(2,2))\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.subplot(1,2,1) # Plot of 1 row 2 columns\n",
    "plt.imshow(hybrid_image, cmap='gray')\n",
    "plt.axis('off') # Get rid of axis for the sake of clarity\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
